{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/diverticular-disease/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"5bcd7ed5-7ab4-57a1-a517-99ee8bb7b2d5","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 74bbc050-484e-43cc-b058-13a6d9b47786 --><h1>Diverticular disease: Summary</h1><!-- end field 74bbc050-484e-43cc-b058-13a6d9b47786 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 8f32c1e6-ab33-4452-9798-e9ba02c6301b --><!-- begin field 6e244109-b10f-41d7-a8fa-73a55a697cc4 --><ul><li>Diverticula are sac-like protrusions of mucosa through the muscular wall of the colon, which occur in the sigmoid colon in about 85% of people over the age of 80. <ul><li>The majority of people have symptoms which are present in the left lower abdomen. </li><li>In a minority of people and in people of Asian origin, symptoms may be right-sided.</li><li>Diverticulum formation may be associated with a low-fibre diet.</li></ul></li><li>Diverticulosis is a condition where diverticula are present without symptoms.<ul><li>It may present with a large, painless rectal bleed, or be found incidentally during investigation for other symptoms.</li></ul></li><li>Diverticular disease is a condition where diverticula cause symptoms, such as intermittent lower abdominal pain, without inflammation and infection.</li><li>Diverticulitis is a condition where diverticula become inflamed and infected, typically causing severe lower abdominal pain, fever, general malaise, change in bowel habit, and occasionally rectal bleeding.<ul><li>'Uncomplicated' diverticulitis refers to localized diverticular inflammation that does not extend to the peritoneum.</li><li>'Complicated' diverticulitis refers to diverticulitis associated with complications, such as rectal bleeding, abscess, peritonitis, fistula, obstruction, or perforation.</li></ul></li><li>The presence of diverticula is rare before the age of 40 years, and the risk increases with age.</li><li>If a person has suspected diverticular disease, a routine referral to a specialist in colorectal surgery should be arranged to confirm the diagnosis.</li><li>If a person has confirmed diverticulosis, management includes:<ul><li>Eating a healthy, balanced, high-fibre diet.</li><li>Drinking an adequate fluid intake.</li></ul></li><li>If a person has confirmed diverticular disease, management includes:<ul><li>Arranging urgent admission if there is significant rectal bleeding.</li><li>Eating a healthy, balanced, high-fibre diet.</li><li>Drinking an adequate fluid intake.</li><li>Encouraging weight loss and smoking cessation, if appropriate.</li><li>Considering prescribing bulk-forming laxatives.</li><li>Advising on the use of analgesia, such as paracetamol as-needed.</li><li>Reviewing the person, depending on clinical judgement, and arranging referral to a specialist in colorectal surgery if there are persistent or refractory symptoms.</li></ul></li><li>Urgent hospital admission should be arranged if there is suspected acute diverticulitis and the person:<ul><li>Has a suspected complication.</li><li>Has symptoms which cannot be managed in primary care.</li><li>Is unable to take or tolerate oral fluids at home.</li><li>Is unable to take or tolerate oral antibiotics (if needed) at home.</li><li>Is frail and/or has significant co-morbidities and/or is immunocompromised.</li></ul></li><li>If a person has suspected mild, uncomplicated diverticulitis, management in primary care includes:<ul><li>Considering prescribing oral antibiotics if there is suspected infection or watchful waiting if the person is systemically well with no co-morbidities.</li><li>Advising on the use of analgesia, such as paracetamol as-needed.</li><li>Recommending clear liquids only, with a gradual reintroduction of solid food if symptoms improve.</li><li>Consider checking bloods for raised white cell count and C-reactive protein (CRP).</li><li>Reviewing the person within 48 hours, or sooner if symptoms worsen.</li></ul></li><li>If a person is managed in primary care and has frequent or severe recurrent episodes of acute diverticulitis, referral to a specialist in colorectal surgery should be considered.</li></ul><!-- end field 6e244109-b10f-41d7-a8fa-73a55a697cc4 --><!-- end item 8f32c1e6-ab33-4452-9798-e9ba02c6301b -->","topic":{"id":"94c44346-c791-5b97-9e45-bacb8fe90589","topicId":"eee234d5-c667-4944-95d2-a45f5e032286","topicName":"Diverticular disease","slug":"diverticular-disease","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"5bcd7ed5-7ab4-57a1-a517-99ee8bb7b2d5","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5abc06b8-fef4-5d67-81ce-ee1c71284864","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"71ba91f6-898b-5f69-bd52-93f3b1892ad6","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"7460514b-3977-52be-9e12-06486604b194","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"909831b0-6f3c-5e85-8263-a5e1785b8a49","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"fcd203c7-5d1a-5fcc-ab90-5286ab76bd2d","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"2cbe6fe5-f942-566e-9136-915145ba8517","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"ffcabc25-6966-526d-8382-a5fcf56185ab","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"dc0b24e2-e0db-5829-baf5-a7aae6d5ab67","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"b5dcfe41-ec7c-5a9f-bc96-229f8b818a77","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"d9311147-ff58-5778-bb86-c0249937ef45","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"5b76632c-4924-5c26-99ab-549b62bb2f73","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"435ea69d-fb08-554b-b803-cc64d393575b","slug":"background-information","fullItemName":"Background info